This year saw Charles Mingus bring gospel harmonies to his modernist arrangements. It also found John Coltrane developing his signature sheets of sound, in addition to appearing on Miles Davis' Kind of Blue. From Dave Brubeck's odd-meter hooks to Ornette Coleman's tart new approach to songwriting, indelible melodies intersected with compositional sophistication in this banner year of American art music.

A virtuoso practically from the cradle, Chris Potter was able to pick up and play seemingly any instrument as a child. The music of Paul Desmond eventually inspired him to focus his energy on the saxophone and by age 13 he was booking professional gigs. After attending the Manhattan School of Music, Potter played with Red Rodney's quintet, as well as the group The Jazz Mentality before launching his solo career. He went on to release several albums and become one of the most vital saxophonists of his generation. Potter was nominated for a GRAMMY® for his work with Joanne Brackeen.

Bassist and composer Michael League feeds his exuberant jazz-fusion crew a constantly rotating cast of tasteful guest players and singers, making Snarky Puppy's jams fascinatingly unpredictable—though reliably rich. Collaborations with Dutch big band Metropole Orkest and American crooner Lalah Hathaway swing the mix from string-drenched funk vamps to Rhodes-and-guitar-driven soul in the style of Steely Dan. And whether executing sensational solos over tempo-shifting instrumentals or sitting back beneath sweet vocals, the Texas-bred group reshapes its ever-changing sound with electronic twists.
